messages.content: 9-1-1, what's your emergency?
I think I need an ambulance. I've got a teenager. He's turning purple in his face. I think he's passed out or something. I don't know.
How old is he?
He's 16.
And you don't know what's wrong with him?
No.
Is he breathing?
I don't know. He's turning purple.
It's 725 Greenwood Circle.
Okay, ma'am. Calm down, okay?
Okay.
Just hang on here with me.
Okay.
Time 1, priority response to 725 Greenwood Circle.
They're giving him mouth to mouth. Hold on.
Does he have asthma or anything? Why is he not breathing?
I don't know.
How long has he not been breathing?
I don't know. He looks bad.
Does he have a pulse?
Not really.
Open his airway slightly and feel for breath over his mouth.
Wait, let me turn the TV off. I can't hear anything.
Okay. Breathe into his mouth, do you feel the air going in?
Let's take an ambulance so long. We're not doing any good here.
They're just now leaving. It's only been like a minute.
What you need to do is try to do CPR. That's going to be the most important thing.
Will you repeat that? My radio is cutting out.
You need to take a full breath in and seal your mouth over his. Did you see his chest rise?
Put the heel of one hand on the center of his breastbone, right between the nipples. Then take your other hand and put it on top of that.
Give him two more breaths, slow and deep. Watch for his chest to rise.
Continue until the ambulance gets there, okay?
If he has a pulse, is he breathing?
No.
When you breathed into his mouth, did his chest rise?
No.
Give him two more breaths. Can you see his chest rise?
He's not cold.
They're very close. They're in the 900 blocks. Continue giving the breaths, okay?
Okay.
You're doing good. Keep going until they arrive.
Sorry, we are on the way. Bye.
